    "summary": "The Umayyad Caliphate (661–750 AD) was the first great Islamic dynasty — the caliphate that transformed the nascent Muslim state into a major world empire extending from the Iberian Peninsula to Central Asia, governing the largest contiguous empire the world had yet seen. Founded by Muawiya I after the First Fitna civil war, the Umayyads moved the capital from Medina to Damascus and adopted elements of Byzantine and Sassanid administrative practice, ruling through Arab tribal networks. Their expansion was breathtaking: the [[event:2131|conquest of Spain]] (711 AD), the reaching of the Indus River in the east, and Central Asian expansion as far as modern Pakistan.\n\nThe Umayyad period saw the construction of the [[event:2130|Dome of the Rock]] (691 AD) in Jerusalem — the first great monument of Islamic architecture — and the development of Islamic coinage, postal systems, and administrative structures. Arabic was established as the sole official language of administration. However, the Umayyads faced persistent criticism for privileging Arab Muslims over non-Arab converts (mawali), creating social tensions that fueled the [[event:3521|Abbasid Revolution]]. Theologically, many Muslims considered the Umayyads impious worldly rulers who had betrayed Muhammad's egalitarian ideals. The dynasty was overthrown in 750 AD by the Abbasids, with the Umayyad family massacred (though one survivor, Abd al-Rahman I, escaped to Spain and founded the [[event:2208|Umayyad Emirate of Cordoba]]). Umayyad Damascus gave Islamic civilization its early administrative and artistic foundations.",
